content: California Home       Tuesday, December 09, 2003                                                                                    POST Home Page                                About California POST                Regulations                Selection &        Recruitment                Training, Certificates        & Services                Library, Clearinghouse & Resources                Bulletins, Publications & Forms                FAQs                Site Map                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     My CA                                                          POST Website                                                                                                                                                                                Frequently Asked Questions                                                                                       POST Entry-Level Test Battery                                                          Test Scoring and Test Score Interpretation                                                                                                         1.                What sort of test results will I receive?                  Users of the test battery receive a computer printout which lists,                for each applicant, total score on the writing tests, total score                on the reading tests, and total score on the entire test battery.                Total score on the writing tests and total score on the reading                tests are expressed both as percents and as "t" scores. Total score                on the entire battery is expressed as a "t" score only. Users also                receive summary information regarding total sample, sample by gender,                sample by ethnicity, and a table which assists in identifying relative                ethnic and gender performance. Three versions of the printout are                generated. On one, information is presented in score order based                on the total T score. In another, information is presented in alpha                order based on candidate last name. And, on the third, information                is ordered according to candidate social security number. Typically,                the user agency receives the score and alpha listings, and POST                retains the social security number listing. When specifically requested,                POST will provide the results on a computer diskette with the data                in ASCII format. It is important to note that the POST Test Battery                scores are expressed as T scores and not the more familiar percent                correct scores. Even though commonly used, percentages have severe                limitations as measures of test performance. While it is possible                to re-scale T scores into a 70-100 range, this is strongly not recommended                as the scores lose their meaning (the user can no longer calculate                percentile equivalents to the "t" scores) and any combining of the                recalibrated scores with other scores will result in  erroneous                 list orders.                                 2. Is there a set or recommended cut                score (passing score) for the test?                No, POST has established neither a mandated nor recommended cut                score for the exam. It is the responsibility of the user agency                to set the cut score. POST has established, however, a recommended                range of scores within which the cut score should be set. This range                is from 40 to 50 based on total test score (Overall T score). POST                research has repeatedly demonstrated that there is a linear relationship,                across the entire range of scores, between the scores on the POST                Test Battery and performance in the academy and on the job. Therefore,                the higher a department sets the cut score the higher the expected                proficiency of those passing. Conversely, the lower the cut score                the lower the expected performance of those passing. Experience                with the test has demonstrated that individuals with Overall T scores                below 40 will frequently either fail the academy or perform marginally.                As is always the case with test predictions, there will be false                negatives and false positives. That is, there will be some individuals                with low test scores for whom failure is predicted but who will                succeed in the academy. And, there will be individuals with passing                test scores for whom success is predicted but who will fail in the                academy. In the long run, however, low scoring individuals will                perform less well than better scoring individuals, and the higher                the test score achieved the greater the probability that the individual                will perform more capably both in the academy and on the job. Care                should be exercised, however, when deciding how high to set a cut                score. For while it is true that higher scores predict higher abilities,                they also tend to increase adverse impact against some protected                groups. Thus, considerations other than just predicted performance                should play a role in deciding on a specific cut score (e.g., the                number of vacancies to be filled, the ethnic make-up of the department,                etc.). One important factor to consider when setting a cut score                is the standard error of measurement for the test. No test is perfectly                reliable; there is always some error in test scores. The standard                error of measurement is an estimate of the magnitude of this error.                For the POST test battery, the standard error is about 3 score units.                This means that for a score of 50, for example, there is a 68 percent                chance that the "true" score is somewhere between 47 (50-3=47) and                53 (50+3=53). Realizing that scores are not error free, one should                be cautious when making distinctions between candidates with extremely                close scores. Presently, the average cut score being set by agencies                is around T=46 and the average cut score being set by college academies                is T=42.                                 3. Should the test be scored pass/fail                or should candidates be ranked?                It is recommended that users of the test battery give serious consideration                to using the scores to rank order candidates. Usually this means                combining the written test score and the oral score. For a detailed                explanation of the proper way to combine written and oral scores                see  Question #6  "What are T Scores? Why use                them rather than percent correct scores?" Extensive research by                POST has shown that scores on the POST Test Battery are highly predictive                of success in the academy and on the job. As test scores increase,                so correspondingly does performance in the academy and performance                on the job. This type of relationship is referred to as a monotonic                relationship and it is shown graphically in Figure 1.                                                  When monotonicity exists, optimal utility for test results is achieved                by ranking individuals based on test score. In scoring a test pass/fail,                one assumes a dichotomous distribution where those below the cut                score are unqualified and those above it are qualified. Once this                assumption has been made, all those below the cut score are regarded                as equally unqualified and all those above it are regard as equally                qualified. No distinctions can be made between individuals within                the two groups. In a dichotomous distribution there is no monotonicity                and no distinction between those above the pass point can be made.                A dichotomous distribution has been graphically depicted in Figure                2.                                                  Given what we empirically know about the results of POST Test Battery,                however, the condition depicted in Figure 2 is clearly incorrect.                There is no point above which improved test score is not accompanied                by improved academy or job performance, and to score the test battery                pass/fail is to ignore valuable information regarding individuals                who score above the minimum cut score. If, for example, a cut score                were set at 40 and the test battery was used pass/fail, then individuals                with scores of 40 through 75 would functionally be considered to                be of equal ability. The validity evidence, however, shows that                this is not the case: higher test scores are associated with higher                levels of performance both in the academy and on the job. To use                the test dichotomously is to lose the vast majority of the information                that the test has to offer.                                 4. Does the test manifest adverse                effect?                The Uniform Guidelines defines adverse impact as the relationship                of passing rates between groups.                               A selection rate for any race, sex, or ethnic group which is                  less than four-fifths (4/5) (or eighty percent) of the rate for                  the group with the highest rate will generally be regarded by                  the Federal enforcement agencies as evidence of adverse impact,                  while a greater than four-fifths rate will generally not be evidence                  of adverse impact.                   Given this definition, adverse effect is a test administration specific     phenomena--a test may manifest adverse effect in one test administration     and not in another.   When defined in this manner, however, it becomes extremely     difficult to discuss the "adverse effect" of a specific test.     Because test      content is obviously constant from one administration to the next, differences       in adverse effect from one administration to another must be due to factors        independent of the test itself.  One needs to identify those factors which      change from one administration to administration in order to understand the       increase or decrease in group differences. It is well established        that tests of cognitive ability (this includes the POST Test Battery)        tend to manifest some degree of adverse effect, but the extent of group         differences is frequently a function of  the locale of the test and       the type of recruitment that assembled the particular group of test       takers.  It is generally the case that adverse impact can be minimized       with careful focused recruitment so that only qualified individuals        from all groups take the test. Conversely, outreach recruitment will        tend to increase adverse impact by involving individuals in the        selection process who may not be as prepared as some others to take        the test.  It is also generally the case that the higher the cut score        the greater will be the adverse impact.  Using test scores to rank         candidates, as opposed to using the test pass/fail, will similarly          tend to increase adverse impact. Regardless of the presence          or absence of adverse impact, however, it is important to note        that statistical analyses have demonstrated that the POST Test        Battery is not "unfair" to protected group individuals.          Differences in test score indicate real differences on job         related skills.                         5. Is There Differential Prediction              for Different Groups?              A Cleary analysis ( Cleary, 1968 )              was conducted to determine whether the test battery is unfair (in              terms of systematically under-predicting achievement) for members              of any protected group. The analysis was computed for each of the              performance criteria. The results of all analyses indicate that the              test is not unfair to protected groups and, in fact, slightly over-predicts              performance of protected group members on all criteria.                                6. What are T scores? Why use them rather              than percent correct scores?                "T" scores are standardized raw test score that have been transformed into a new scale of measurement with a mean of 50 and a standard deviation of 10.  The "t" scale is one of the most widely used of the derived scales.  It has a convenient mean, unit, and standard deviation. Further, controlling the mean and the standard deviation of the distribution makes accurate weighting of scores possible.   Scoring a test is simple, properly interpreting test results is not.  To score a test one need only total the number of items that a test-taker gets correct.  The purposes of personnel selection, however, go beyond merely summing correct responses.  Decisions must be made regarding what different scores mean; good test performance must be distinguished from poor test performance.  Somewhere in the test process, scores are usually combined, either scores from different segments or components of a single test (as POST does with its reading and writing test segments) or scores from different test procedures (as is done when written and oral tests are combined).  Ultimately, a cut score must be set and test-takers classified into those considered qualified and those considered not qualified.  It is in this interpretation and combining of scores that significant problems can be encountered.  The following is a short discussion of some of the issues relevant to interpreting test scores and to the ways that standardizing scores improves this interpretation.  If raw correct responses are simply summed, very little useful information is generated.  In fact, a total raw score absent other information is almost totally useless.  How would one interpret a score of 35, or 76, or 103?  Without other information (such as the total number of items, average performance, score variance, etc.) no real interpretation is possible.  Calculating percentages helps a little, but only a little.  Percentages eliminate (to a limited degree) the need to know the total number of items, but they still do not reveal average performance or score variance.  Even, however, if one possesses a percentage or raw score, a distribution mean, and a distribution standard deviation, one still does not have a convenient procedure for interpreting and using this information.  Enter the standard score.  In essence, a standard score converts a raw or percentage score into a distance--the distance of a particular score from the mean score expressed in standard deviation units.  Thus, a standard score incorporates all available relevant information into a single unit.  And, by putting each individual score in the distribution of scores, one can know exactly how each score relates to all others.  Interpreting a score as a position in a distribution of scores is necessitated by the limitations of the types of values generated by certain types of tests.  Consider the difference between stating that a man weighs 200 pounds and that he scored 50% on a language ability test.  The first measure has meaning while the second does not.  The reason for this difference is due to the differences in the scales of measurement that are used to evaluate weight and to evaluate language ability.  We know how much a pound is, and we know that two pounds are exactly twice as many and one pound.  Further, we know that a man who weighs 200 pounds on one scale will weigh the same on another scale, assuming they are both accurate.  We can conclude these things because the measurement of weight is characterized by equal intervals between units of measurement and because the unit of measurement itself is independent of particular instruments used for the evaluation of weight.  A pound is a pound regardless of the scale used for measurement, and two pounds always weighs exactly twice as much as one pound.  The conclusions that one can make regarding the evaluation of language ability are considerably different from those one can make regarding the evaluation of weight.  Taken by itself, a language score of 50% is totally meaningless.  This is because the evaluation of ability (the score) is completely a function of the test on which it was generated (as contrasted to measurements of height and weight which are independent of the measurement device).  There are no units of language ability that are independent of language tests in the same way that units of weight are independent of individual scales.  Further, a person who takes different language tests will invariably score differently on each test.   This is expected because of the absence of absolute units of language ability and because of differences in test focus and difficulty.  Subsequently, the intervals between units of language ability are not equal as are units of measurement of weight.  A score of 50 does not indicate twice the language ability of a score of 25 in the sense that 50 pounds is twice as much as 25 pounds.  Because the units of measurement on psychological variables do not have the clear and precise meaning characterized by measures of physical objects does not mean that they have no meaning.  It does, however, require that a different strategy for deriving meaning from measurement be developed.  Since the unit of measurement on a psychological test cannot transcend or become independent of the test from which it was generated, the meaning that can be attached to a test score must be distilled from the distribution of scores itself.  For a test score (on a psychological test) to be interpretable, that score must be presented in a manner that describes its position  in the total distribution of scores.  It is the position of the score in the distribution that is the basis for all meaning in psychological measurement.  The procedure that accomplishes this is standardization.  A standard score is a transformation of a raw score or a percentage score to a new value in a way that utilizes the mean as the reference point for the distribution of scores, the standard deviation as the basis for defining the units of measurement, and the individual scores to  locate specific points in the distribution.  The reason for using the mean and standard deviation is that they provide the best summary description of the distribution.  The mean is a measure of central tendency; it is the best single description of the scores that make up the distribution of scores.  The standard deviation is a measure of dispersion; it is the most dependable estimate of the variability in the distribution of scores.  The individual raw scores comprise the actual points in the distribution.  The standard score takes each of these values into account--the mean, the standard deviation, and the individual scores.  There are various different standard scores but only two will be discussed here, z scores and "t" scores.  The simplest standard score is the z score; it has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.  The formula for z is:                              Z = (X-M)/SD                   Where             X = a raw score or   a percentage score                                 M = the mean value   of the distribution                                 SD = the standard   deviation of the distribution                           Table 1 demonstrates how percentages are converted to Z scores.                                              Table 1                               The Transformation   of Test Scores                               Expressed as   Percentages to Z                               Test Scores             Conversion to                               Expressed as   Percents             Z Scores                               55             (55-65)/5 = -2                               60             (60-65)/5 = -1                               65             (65-65)/5 =  0                   X= 65             70             (70-65)/5 =  1                   SD = 5             75             (75-65)/5 =  2                                  Notice that the standards scores contain all of the relevant information        necessary to position scores in the distribution.  Once a raw score or      percentage score has been transformed into a standard score, reference      is made to the normal curve to position that score precisely in the distribution      of scores.            The normal curve represents a distribution with known characteristics.       What makes the normal curve so useful in personnel testing is that       it allows one to determine the proportion of scores above and below a        particular score.  Figure 3 summarizes the areas under the normal curve.                              From this table one can readily see that including the cases           one standard deviation on both sides of the mean will account          for 68% of the total cases (34% + 34% =  68%).  Two standard           deviations will account for approximately 96% of the cases           (14% + 34% +34% +14% = 96%).  Notice that both the normal curve           and the standard scores are calibrated in standard deviation units.          This makes z scores directly interpretable from the normal curve.            For example, a z score of 1 is 1 standard deviation below the          mean.  Fourteen percent of all cases fall below this value          and  86% of the cases are above it.   A z score of +1 would           have 86% of cases below it and 14% above it.  For a table           containing standard scores and the corresponding percentile            equivalents, click here.                While z scores are easily referenced to the normal curve, distributions converted        to z invariably contain very small, negative numbers which are cumbersome in      personnel work.    Because of this, T scores have become the convention when      reporting test scores.  A T score distribution has a mean of 50 and a standard       deviation of 10.  T scores are easily computed from z scores by multiplying       the z score by 10 and then adding 50.  Table 3 demonstrates this using the same       example scores as were used in Table 1.                                    Table 3                               Transformation of   Test Scores from Percentages to Z Scores                               and then to T   Scores                               Test Scores   Expressed             Test Scores   Expressed As             Z Scores Converted                                As Percents             Z Scores             To T Scores                               55             -2             -2(10)+50 = 30                               60             -1             -1(10)+50 = 40                               65             0             0(10)+50 = 50                               70             1             1(10)+50 = 60                               75             2             2(10)+50 = 70                   Mean = 65                                                       SD = 5                                                             Considering what is required for a score to be interpretable, it becomes        obvious why raw scores and percentage scores are so inadequate as indices of        test performance.  They contain none of the necessary information for identifying        the placement of scores in the distribution.  All that they convey is the number        of correct responses.  In contrast, by converting raw scores or percentage scores        to standard scores, the precise position of each score in the distribution can be        known relative to all other scores in the distribution.  Given the limitations        inherent in psychological measurement, this is the optimum information that can        be deduced from test scores.                 In addition to problems of score interpretation, there are also problems        relating to the combining of scores.  For scores from two or more tests or      sub-tests to be accurately combined, the means and variances of those tests      and sub-tests must be identical.  It is only when this condition exists that      the stated weights of the various components actually become the achieved      weights in the composite score.  When the means and variances are not identical,      the achieved weight never corresponds with the stated weights.  An example       clarifies this point.  In Table 4 tests with identical means and different       standard deviations are standardized to z to show the effect of standard       deviation size on the transformed score.  Then, in Table 5, hypothetical       data is presented for five candidates on two tests.  This table will show       how rank order is affected when test scores with unequal variances        are combined.                                    Table 4                   Transformed Scores   Based on Tests with                   Identical Means and   Different Standard Deviations                   % Score                         z Score             T Score             T Score                   Test             z Score SD=5             SD=10             SD=5              SD=10                    55             -2             -1.0             30             40                    60             -1             -.5             40             45                   65             0             0             50             50                   70             1             .5             60             55                   75             2             1.0             70             60                                            Mean for both tests=65                                From this example it becomes clear that the transformed scores from       tests with identical means and different standard deviations are identical       only at the mean, where one expect them to be identical.  At all other scores,       the transformed scores are different and a function of the size of the standard        deviations of their respective distributions.  Clearly, the smaller the standard        deviation, the larger the differences in transformed scores when the test means      are the same. In the following Table, the effects on score combining of      different standard deviations are reflected in a different manner.  This      Table contains the scores of two individuals who take the same two tests.       The tests have identical means but different standard deviations.  Compare       the total scores as expressed as percentages and as "t" scores.                      Table 5                   Differences in List Placement                    Due to Different Standard Deviations                               Test Candidate 1             Test Candidate 2                                 Z Scores             To T Scores                   Test A              -2             -2(10)+50 = 30                   Test B             -1             -1(10)+50 = 40                   Total Score              0             0(10)+50 = 50                                                                 Mean of both tests = 65                    Test A SD=5                    Test B SD=10                        Both candidates scored 55% and 65% on the tests; the only difference is       the particular test on which the different scores were achieved.          Looking at the Total Score row of the Table, it can be seen that both candidates       achieved identical Total Percentage Score (115%), but they achieved different        Total T Scores (75 and 85).   If one were to score the test using percents        and tie the two individuals an error would have been made because the two         candidates did, in fact, have different scores.  When the tests are scored         correctly, Candidate 2 outperforms Candidate 1 by 10 standard score units.        Table 6 presents a more realistic situation describing a test administration         with 5 candidates on 2 tests.  Again, the means of the two tests are the same,         and the standard deviations are different.  As can be readily seen from this       Table, it is impossible to generate an accurate list order in the absence of        standard scores.                                Table 6    Comparison of Candidate Ranking that Result from    Different Procedures for Combining Scores                                               Test A             Test B             Total             Ranking                   Candidate             T             %   T             %   T             %   T             %                   1             4             71   32             100   70             86   51             1                   2             3             77   44             89   59             83   52             3                   3             5             80   50             80   50             80   50             5                   4             2             90   70             74   44             82   57             4                   5             1             95   80             73   43             84   62             2                   Test A   Mean=80, SD=5    Test B   Mean=80, SD=10    Total   (.5*A) + (.5*B)     NOTE: The means and standard deviations for test A and B   are hypothetical and are not the means and standard deviations for the five   cases in the table.                                  Comparing the rank order of candidates based on weighted percents       and weighted standard scores reveals significant differences.  In       the above example, the scores from Test A are weighted 50% and the       scores from Test B are weighted 50%.  When scores are not standardized,       the test with the larger standard deviation will receive a disproportionate       amount of the weight in the combined total.              It should be noted that differences in means will also result in       different transformed scores for the same raw or percentage score.         Thus, differences in either means or variances precludes accurate        score combining.  In the real world, it is almost always the case        that both the means and standard deviations of two tests will differ        significantly.  When this occurs, and scores are not standardized,        it is literally impossible to predict the types of errors that are        created when scores are weighted and combined. In summary, there are        two primary reasons why converting to standard scores is essential      in personnel testing.  First, for a test score to be interpretable,       the score must be presented in a manner that identifies its position       in the total distribution of scores.  And second, for scores from two        tests to be accurately combined into a total or summary score, the         means and variances of the two tests must be taken into account.          In the absence of standardized test scores, neither correct score         interpretation nor accurate combining of scores can be achieved.                                                                                                                                 Back to Top of Page         © 2003 State of California           Conditions of Use         The content found herein may not necessarily represent the views and opinions of the Schwarzenegger Administration.
